XIII. 1 Among things, land first occurs. This is recovered by postliminium, when the enemy are expelled : that is, when the enemy can no longer openly approach the land. So the Lacedoemonians, when they had taken Egina from the Athenians, restored it to its ancient owners. Justinian gave the lands taken from the Goths and Vandals to the heirs of the old possessors, not admitting contrary pre- scriptions.

2 What is true of lands, is true of all rights adhering to the soil. So places which had been consecrated as religious, if liberated, resume their former state: as Cicero argues against Verres, of the Diana of Segeste. Marcion compares the right of postliminium to that by which, when a house tumbles down, the soil is restored to the shore.
